nnot change any number to 3 since 3 > limit.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,1,2], limit = 2\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: nums is already complementary.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= limit <= 10⁵`\n\n- `n` is even.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Hash Table","Prefix Sum"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given an integer array `nums` of **even** length `n` and an integer `limit`. In one move, you can replace any integer from `nums` with another integer between `1` and `limit`, inclusive.\n\nThe array `nums` is **complementary** if for all indices `i` (**0-indexed**), `nums[i] + nums[n - 1 - i]` equals the same number. For example, the array `[1,2,3,4]` is complementary because for all indices `i`, `nums[i] + nums[n - 1 - i] = 5`.\n\nReturn the ***minimum** number of moves required to make *`nums`* **complementary***.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,4,3], limit = 4\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: In 1 move, you can change nums to [1,2,2,3] (underlined elements are changed).\nnums[0] + nums[3] = 1 + 3 = 4.\nnums[1] + nums[2] = 2 + 2 = 4.\nnums[2] + nums[1] = 2 + 2 = 4.\nnums[3] + nums[0] = 3 + 1 = 4.\nTherefore, nums[i] + nums[n-1-i] = 4 for every i, so nums is complementary.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,2,1], limit = 2\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: In 2 moves, you can change nums to [2,2,2,2]. You cannot change any number to 3 since 3 > limit.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,1,2], limit = 2\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: nums is already complementary.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= limit <= 10⁵`\n\n- `n` is even.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-moves-to-make-array-complementary/","problemName":"Minimum Moves to Make Array Complementary","problemNumber":1674,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an integer array `nums` of **even** length `n` and an integer `limit`. In one move, you can replace any integer from `nums` with another integer between `1` and `limit`, inclusive.\n\nThe array `nums` is **complementary** if for all indices `i` (**0-indexed**), `nums[i] + nums[n - 1 - i]` equals the same number. For example, the array `[1,2,3,4]` is complementary because for all indices `i`, `nums[i] + nums[n - 1 - i] = 5`.\n\nReturn the ***minimum** number of moves required to make *`nums`* **complementary***.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,4,3], limit = 4\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: In 1 move, you can change nums to [1,2,2,3] (underlined elements are changed).\nnums[0] + nums[3] = 1 + 3 = 4.\nnums[1] + nums[2] = 2 + 2 = 4.\nnums[2] + nums[1] = 2 + 2 = 4.\nnums[3] + nums[0] = 3 + 1 = 4.\nTherefore, nums[i] + nums[n-1-i] = 4 for every i, so nums is complementary.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,2,1], limit = 2\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: In 2 moves, you can change nums to [2,2,2,2]. You cannot change any number to 3 since 3 > limit.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: nums = [1,2,1,2], limit = 2\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: nums is already complementary.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= nums[i] <= limit <= 10⁵`\n\n- `n` is even.","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Medium","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"You are given an integer array `nums` of **even** length `n` and an integer `limit`. In one move, you can replace any integer from `nums` with another integer between `1` an